{"id":"cond-mat/0504307","submitter":"Alexander G. Abanov","authors":"Alexander G. Abanov","title":"Hydrodynamics of correlated systems. Emptiness Formation Probability and\n  Random Matrices","comments":"25 pages, 2 figures. This is an extended version of the seminar given\n  at the School \"Applications of Random Matrices in Physics\", Les Houches, June\n  2004","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el cond-mat.stat-mech","license":null,"abstract":"  A hydrodynamic approach is used to calculate an asymptotics of the Emptiness\nFormation Probability - the probability of a formation of an empty space in the\nground state of a quantum one-dimensional many body system. Quantum\nhydrodynamics of a system is represented as a Euclidian path integral over\nconfigurations of hydrodynamic variables. In the limit of a large size of the\nempty space, the probability is dominated by an instanton configuration, and\nthe problem is reduced to the finding of an instanton solution of classical\nhydrodynamic equations. After establishing a general formalism, we carry out\nthis calculation for several simple systems -- free fermions with an arbitrary\ndispersion and Calogero-Sutherland model. For these systems we confirm the\nobtained results by comparison with exact results known in Random Matrix\ntheory. We argue that the nonlinear hydrodynamic approach might be useful even\nin cases where the linearized hydrodynamics fails.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 12 Apr 2005 20:18:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
